{
  "text": "Exposure of eukaryotes to chemical toxins induces the expression of detoxification enzymes and transporters that modify and excrete these xenobiotics [CITATION_1] . Because inactivation by RNA interference (RNAi) of genes that encode targets of natural toxins also induces detoxification responses, surveillance of the core cellular processes such as translation, electron transport and so on, rather than detection of toxins through their molecular signatures, may detect toxic and pathogen attacks and couple to the induction of defence responses [CITATION_2] . Sentinel cells that detect xenobiotics could induce a protective systemic response. A prediction of this cellular surveillance model is that disruption of such core processes even by a host mutation in such components should be interpreted by this system as a toxic attack and cause induction of detoxification and immunity genes. Here, we report that a variety of mutation-induced defects that disrupt translation only in the Caenorhabditis elegans germline trigger the induction of detoxification and innate immune gene expression in the intestine, the organ most likely to encounter bacterial pathogens. Laser ablation of germline stem cells abrogates this xenobiotic response to germline-translation-defective mutations, showing that germ cells are the signalling centre. An RNAi screen for genes that are required for the induction of xenobiotic response genes after exposure to drugs that inhibit translation or in response to mutations that disable germline translation revealed a kinase cascade and a lipid biosynthetic pathway that generates systemic signals of impaired translation. Purified mammalian bile acids can rescue the signalling defects in the lipid-biosynthesis-gene-inactivated animals, suggesting that the signals of translational malaise are bile acid derivatives. Particular bacterial species from a panel that we tested can suppress these host surveillance and detoxification pathways, showing that these pathways are targets of bacterial modulation.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "14402974",
    "[CITATION_2]": "16995253"
